(chapter
  :book "Book of ML"
  :chapter-number 0
  :title "Cover — building a language model from nothing"
  :audience "kid-and-adult operators, curious programmers"
  :dialect "motoi"
  :voice "motoi-copilot"
  :training-eligible #t
  :confidentiality "public"
  :provenance
    (:authored-at "2026-07-19"
     :authored-by "book-of-ml-author-agent"
     :sources ((:doctrine "project_motoi_is_the_new_speak_and_spell_2026_07_17")
               (:doctrine "project_motoi_bridge_to_claude_11_year_old_frame_2026_07_17")
               (:doctrine "project_motoi_personality_2026_07_17")
               (:reference "MOTOI-SCHEME-REFERENCE.slat" :section "vec/, matrix/, math/, random")
               (:paper "Vaswani et al. 2017 — Attention Is All You Need"
                :arxiv "1706.03762"
                :used-for "chapters 12-16")
               (:paper "Rumelhart, Hinton, Williams 1986 — Learning representations by back-propagating errors"
                :used-for "chapter 9")
               (:paper "Sennrich et al. 2015 — Neural Machine Translation of Rare Words with Subword Units (BPE)"
                :arxiv "1508.07909"
                :used-for "chapter 15"))
     :spec-source "self"
     :runtime-source "src/base.js + src/vec.js + src/matrix.js")
  :prose
"# The Book of ML

You are going to build a language model.

Not use one. Not talk to one. Build one. In Scheme. On your own machine.
Sixteen chapters from now, you will type a program into the REPL and it
will read a small book and finish a sentence you gave it. The math will
be math you did by hand. The code will be code you typed. You will know
what a language model is because you will have made one.

That is what this book is for.

## Who this is for

A curious kid with an afternoon. A working programmer who has used LLMs
and never seen inside one. Someone who has heard the words attention,
embedding, transformer, and would like to know what they actually mean
in code. Anyone who is tired of magic and would rather have mechanics.

You need to know a little Motoi Scheme. Book of Sick Composition and
Book of R7RS Recipes are the on-ramps. If you can define a function,
run a list through `map`, and understand what `(+ 1 2)` returns, you
are ready.

You do NOT need to know linear algebra or calculus already. Appendix A
teaches the parts you need in the voice of this book, no lecture. You
do NOT need Python, PyTorch, numpy, or a GPU. Motoi runs on the
machine you already have.

## What you will build

By chapter 16 you will have a runnable tiny language model. It will be
small — small enough that it fits in a few hundred lines of Scheme,
small enough that it trains on a few paragraphs of text on a laptop.
It will not be smart. It will not know the world. It will however
finish a sentence, and it will do so by the same mechanics a large
model uses. Different scale. Same shape.

The tiny LLM in chapter 16 uses:

- Tokens and embeddings you built in chapter 11.
- Attention you built in chapter 12.
- A transformer block you built in chapter 13.
- Positional encoding and causal masking from chapter 14.
- The training loop from chapter 10.
- The backprop from chapter 9.
- Gradient descent from chapter 6.

Every part traces to a chapter. If you skip a chapter, you will not
understand a part of the final model. Read them in order.

## The build-up

Each chapter adds one idea. The idea uses only what came before plus
the base Motoi verbs you already have. The idea ends with a runnable
capstone you can type into the REPL and see happen.

That last part matters. Every chapter has a Speak & Spell moment — a
small program short enough to type by hand, that when you press enter,
does the thing. If it does not do the thing, the chapter failed. Tell
me and I will fix it.

## The voice

I am Motoi, and I will explain everything from first principles. I am
not going to say things like 'as an AI language model.' I am going to
say things like 'here is how it works, watch.' I will be dry sometimes.
I will be wrong sometimes about my own limits and I will tell you when
I am. If a thing is not known, I will say so.

Two things I will never do. I will never fabricate math I cannot show
you. I will never write code I have not verified against the Motoi
runtime. Everything in this book runs.

## The 16 chapters

1. **Numbers, tensors, and how a computer counts things**
2. **Vectors and the dot product**
3. **Matrices and matrix-vector multiplication**
4. **Functions of functions — the composition is the network**
5. **What is a model — from a line to a curve**
6. **Gradient descent by hand**
7. **A single neuron**
8. **A layer, then two layers**
9. **Backpropagation from calculus first-principles**
10. **The training loop**
11. **Tokens and embeddings**
12. **Attention as a soft-lookup**
13. **A transformer block**
14. **Positional encoding and causal masking**
15. **Stacking blocks and tokenization**
16. **The tiny LLM**

## The 4 appendices

- **A. Math prerequisites in the Motoi voice.**
- **B. The philosophy of the field — Turing to attention.**
- **C. Why LLMs hallucinate.**
- **D. What you built vs. what I am.**

## Rules of the road

- Every code sample runs. If yours doesn't, the copy-paste dropped a paren.
- Every math step is shown. If you can't follow, back up one paragraph.
- Every claim traces. If I cite a paper, I name it and say why.
- No hand-waving. If I say a thing works, we build the thing that works.

## A runtime note about vectors and lists

In Motoi Scheme, a plain list of numbers IS a vector. All `vec/`
verbs (`vec/dot`, `vec/add`, `vec/scale`, `vec/norm`, `vec/ref`,
`vec/dim`) accept lists directly. So `(vec/dot (list 1 2 3) (list 4
5 6))` returns `32`.

`vec/make` is friendly in both directions. Variadic: `(vec/make 1 2 3)`
builds a 3-vector. List-arg: `(vec/make (list 1 2 3))` also builds a
3-vector — same result. Both forms are in the runtime. Every code
sample in this book runs as written.

Trig lives at `math/*`: `math/sin`, `math/cos`, `math/tan`, `math/atan2`,
`math/asin`, `math/acos`, `math/atan`. The older `geom/*` spellings
still work as aliases so prior carts don't break — but `math/*` is the
canonical name and the one the book uses.

Scientific notation is a number: `1e-5`, `1.5e10`, `-2E-3` all parse.
Learning-rate constants read the way you'd write them on paper.

Multi-list `map` works the R7RS way: `(map + (list 1 2 3) (list 10 20 30))`
returns `(11 22 33)`. Every gradient-step and every layer forward pass
in this book uses that shape.

One last note about alists (small but important). Motoi's `cons`
produces proper lists — `(cons 'a 5)` is the two-element list
`('a 5)`, not the R5RS dotted pair `('a . 5)`. So a vocab entry
built as `(cons \"cat\" 1)` reads as `(\"cat\" 1)`, and the value is
retrieved via `(cadr entry)`, not `(cdr entry)`. If you copy an
alist recipe from an R7RS book and it doesn't run, this is usually
the reason — swap `cdr` for `cadr` where the code reads the value.
Every alist in this book uses the Motoi convention throughout.

Let's begin.
")
